6Am6Ed6iMxkafnNw7ZOlU5pkurVitnJ9Pmcw50EkYMK78hIEmH_x58eXV3Bw12A0TCc0QhMrUeTTQOprbHu-kT9KmPU0i7JbHpg2FaPX1L9cBr8VIGu85aEp_hlD1nElNsb21btpEpaY267eiJFXzlqF0a1RwbYzgBgxt_d0u6tjH_W7O8SAW31nOqnwlL0rYqsvaNO5shRa753yy166K-MTFWRFfofmHbr-0sP92Bt3D9o__CMlGwldgFuQg-fvrXdOOUAgtSic9aNRzgRo-wNHn030D_yCfMtjJ0jghHKCFhlGluBkRsHTrRsJ6zrG6g9gFqlnuA_VgNcRqUJKzDxGQfhJ4Tbc0G-IzlbXXbn98eeOLJhg5F7RiwTaQvHVEoCGFPcMDq9HjGqiymYGybJPOvvmxIpu6wI9KwNT0FURhr3rhz0kuwBRypRfZ0Yh5XHjHF72nvg9mmO2QCT2V7h79ushNlub57ktUGS8yuhtmNWUaKSN6xV_OHp1I5vpJN2t_KDBdAbjeYvuys834q5MiXcOSusFiSyC8Kd2ZhZBVzb7yX-ITEBcg-iLUktc1CyLRWtBEEuFTtE0HSTIlJZV9n9D5pZJRGvjV2QxwxIIoIk4PG_321EBhO2b_FsKaYtAOUwT9i3J3Vx_NMU0jvH32OyTZuIxuHVx5BVolynO2niWNXn9_A92t6Dumka9kyd6vSqcM1UT43XLPbSk_nnNbr91ePK5JzuFfBEj-DFOrBkfFmxc8MMccBOyq5mBljIGSbV5M-T8No5Rqwohv1VCM_L3MslmQNGfIefrNHWYDpaav3q4w5So5pkK_jzp3fiHkfSQo-3DjDmwn1Fufs4EPPN_pe5xf1nhz6oNDtSnpuXo7Gf4F3JJRCig0-yXInEb2KCE1GJBx1BrNZkIh6Vx8Zt2cDhQD88cKq4uOj\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering dynamic class loading in tests**\\n\\nI'm looking at whether the class is already in the image, and if it should work, maybe. There's this optional dynamic discovery in getCatalogResolver that uses dynamic class loading. The rule says I need to catch errors and verify, but I wonder if this is one. It's loading optional resolver classes from the classpath. In Native Image, should I catch errors? If I swallow the error, coverage won't measure correctly. I’m contemplating wrapping test bodies around the error catch to ensure coverage metrics are accurate.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating error handling for tests**\\n\\nThe rule indicates I shouldn't skip native checks and should only catch UnsupportedFeatureError. There's an existing AntClassLoader test, and I'm thinking about adding a helper function, `runWithNativeUnsupportedFeatureCheck`, but it risks swallowing all tests if unsupported features arise. That might be acceptable for resolving the first external resolver. However, I worry that catching errors could mask missing metadata, especially if errors relate to unsupported class loading. It's a tricky balance to strike!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing dynamic class loading tests**\\n\\nI see that the class discovery is dynamic but known, and existing tests around `forceLoadClass` only catch certain issues. Since the dynamic loading of the optional resolver should work with metadata, failing in native due to UnsupportedFeature is acceptable. However, if it fails before covering dynamic calls, that's a concern since dynamic access reports typically come from the JVM. The user instructed to use catch for dynamic class loading, so I think including it makes sense, even though it introduces a dependency on `NativeImageSupport`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating compilation dependencies**\\n\\nI’m considering that the native-image compile probably uses testRuntimeClasspath. I’m wondering if the Ant jar compile has unresolved optional classes, but it seems like Gradle can handle tests with the Ant jar even if it references absent classes, like org.apache.xml. Since javac only loads the classes it references, it’s not an issue. It looks like having everything in testImplementation works just fine. I'll need to check if I have the correct dependency string in build.gradle.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented coverage-focused changes for `org.apache.tools.ant.types.XMLCatalog$ExternalResolver`.\n\nChanged files:\n- `tests/src/ant/ant/1.6/src/test/java/ant/ant/XMLCatalogInnerExternalResolverTest.java`\n  - Added a dedicated public test class for the inner active class.\n  - Covers external catalog processing via public `XMLCatalog` APIs.\n  - Exercises:\n    - external resolver initialization,\n    - external catalog path parsing,\n    - delegated entity resolution for matching and unmatched entries,\n    - delegated URI resolution for matching and unmatched entries.\n\n- `tests/src/ant/ant/1.6/build.gradle`\n  - Added `xml-resolver:xml-resolver:1.2` as a test dependency so Ant’s optional Apache XML resolver bridge is available.\n\nPer instruction, I did not compile or run tests.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_029e33bf58fa4e850169f544860d80819c9610c17c7934ab19\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 544, "output": 1729, "cacheRead": 68096, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 70369, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1777681517171, "responseId": "resp_029e33bf58fa4e850169f5446dc0d4819ca2597ec863c47c00"}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering dynamic class loading in tests**\n\nI'm looking at whether the class is already in the image, and if it should work, maybe. There's this optional dynamic discovery in getCatalogResolver that uses dynamic class loading. The rule says I need to catch errors and verify, but I wonder if this is one. It's loading optional resolver classes from the classpath. In Native Image, should I catch errors? If I swallow the error, coverage won't measure correctly. I’m contemplating wrapping test bodies around the error catch to ensure coverage metrics are accurate.\n\n**Evaluating error handling for tests**\n\nThe rule indicates I shouldn't skip native checks and should only catch UnsupportedFeatureError. There's an existing AntClassLoader test, and I'm thinking about adding a helper function, `runWithNativeUnsupportedFeatureCheck`, but it risks swallowing all tests if unsupported features arise. That might be acceptable for resolving the first external resolver. However, I worry that catching errors could mask missing metadata, especially if errors relate to unsupported class loading. It's a tricky balance to strike!\n\n**Analyzing dynamic class loading tests**\n\nI see that the class discovery is dynamic but known, and existing tests around `forceLoadClass` only catch certain issues. Since the dynamic loading of the optional resolver should work with metadata, failing in native due to UnsupportedFeature is acceptable. However, if it fails before covering dynamic calls, that's a concern since dynamic access reports typically come from the JVM. The user instructed to use catch for dynamic class loading, so I think including it makes sense, even though it introduces a dependency on `NativeImageSupport`.\n\n**Evaluating compilation dependencies**\n\nI’m considering that the native-image compile probably uses testRuntimeClasspath. I’m wondering if the Ant jar compile has unresolved optional classes, but it seems like Gradle can handle tests with the Ant jar even if it references absent classes, like org.apache.xml. Since javac only loads the classes it references, it’s not an issue. It looks like having everything in testImplementation works just fine. I'll need to check if I have the correct dependency string in build.gradle.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_029e33bf58fa4e850169f5446e9658819c9d38e8b6b92fe253\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9USGz-ZLvpJZ33C3cUp6XEyUroLxsY-MQL_lJHHOvDOS11ZsOlJCM0GWgY8Temzvf_AR_w-lNPyrMJK18HsLEEFspSXtkvsD1811dxwnbYBMZtnXDY8ZRzDNfKuZvxtkI_ZlNxmiZUc1uzQCfxjPFGSJyEeQM8mQmrGM9m7GA8pyxSu1yHm-XD-3ssfpJEHBGBrWm4H2pys39_A-6tTSHGnDbOnWc7Vjo_9kBKV2wK1Roe632JkbptcxZ1Ay9O7V0Gs7v-bqUy8i5ciyip8oxAqFK25x-bfoYCnr4NlQZsrhDegTFs8FUk80hVdeaGIzDSw4WITw2hGpgSWw-6kbk_aL1FHqe8tBSyGjh6KQlsf8GiUZyJOlBFq1hg4lYNAAsCyhaP1iBdqxm_r3xpiiE6SixL6YOHLderhEPxwgMHVc7f-0MAr-IkVGGWQGFS4ztg9JQX_x8MFzgFO5lNvoBNAe4kkDffuMitOrbXC80H4XVqaX-msf2FAqYE37muVlssGM_7I0Tl0l_e6JsXXzJtOsLP5l3Ts6BMF-rWr_jma7nSYBc_Oy_j34n22yjVws1weDSll6FdVliQ-nsv4PZEv5h7Q4aEkt9qt41uUSLJtqMicq8jDdYB8jCSFy-ULY_lbDeAPJV1rDnDmirdTYPJnwZ2S0DZBv_OwOOwW4iA_6VF5EdaATT3fXbk9Pug_F-6PAsAJJhOHOtmq8jpWsGGVxxeUZb5ZJx4s3KqRxVCL7v9I2fBbwdmve1lqmTKSPPFsmkcjc8ongzQCXkXNIx2NT_HOaivKB5tXUATxnLcnVqb-QZVfURiVuqR8VH9yHaOY2GELWo6HEVzpjtmKgvAGJ5Ww0kT54LHwhxYFZL54B7F2OsZi7frmcBhcDNCOz4JCiAt_Us5qlp8hj1D_ZrVHnw9YHpSXYWW80xBaokYEU2SH54G7uAsevoxIlA-pkWSN6fRSeYXTWffDjOLeREKh85hWK__LKrAqS6m3Vu91PlyZ-4guzXIhmx7kNGzCQDeSMEbKMP42QfinLgpB10FlIGSdVQMs8VLv5vZKU7RhO0lhWqQHPz5zaqc1TmRar_bykZQJdVSp-39xmvTkvL3ohR-SrMoyCDIzcuxqtkwNb4-J37JYZQvoiBgq3EmTFoka56pE5zxk6ZtAWoNVTqd0CbtJHUNRsYnG0Chq6eu2cL9YZ3k-CkxZ_wvYaaM48xW0Nlnq_RnKIWep-ybxsPcBxcL9la0v_XuteBoPuoVxQ9tzG3FpmZ1x1eziXTmCPsdyAeucofO_b_DfFGWjbEcXsn79xw1FLvGChFqjHEZ6-wpGGJdQ97ZWuN63I1o8X0ahsoXiNYNLX2EGVKRfJk-jv1P2Ff6-h0jM2ups5LCb3OfW-Peo5bSzKTL3SK0bc62oSnvgnW3YoQZpdRzCjRnpzYGm6DH3wp0PcMTFPKvXczi6G9cRh0CXl-AN4sUMxMV8U848lob1UY